Requirements
A LAN (Ethernet) cable (preferably a crossover cable, but most modern PCs work with standard cables).
PC-1: Has internet access (Wi-Fi or other).
PC-2: Needs internet through LAN.
Steps
1. Connect the PCs
Plug one end of the LAN cable into PC-1 and the other end into PC-2.
2. Enable Internet Sharing on PC-1
Go to Control Panel > Network and Internet > Network and Sharing Center > Change adapter settings.
Right-click on the internet-connected adapter (e.g., Wi-Fi), select Properties.
Go to the Sharing tab.
Check the box: Allow other network users to connect through this computer’s internet connection.
From the dropdown, select the Ethernet/LAN connection (the one connected to PC-2).
Click OK.
3. Set PC-2 to Obtain IP Automatically
On PC-2, go to Control Panel > Network and Internet > Network and Sharing Center > Change adapter settings.
Right-click the Ethernet adapter > Properties.
Double-click Internet Protocol Version 4 (TCP/IPv4).
Select Obtain an IP address automatically and Obtain DNS server address automatically.
Click OK.
4. Verify Connection
On PC-2, open a browser and try to access the internet.
If it doesn’t work, restart both PCs and check cables/adapters.
Troubleshooting Tips
Disable any VPN on PC-1 while sharing.
Temporarily disable Windows Firewall if connection fails.
Use the command ipconfig in Command Prompt (on both PCs) to check network status.
